Pre-heat your #oven{} to 200 degrees. Scrub (but don't peel) the @sweet potato{1} and chop into 3cm chunks. Peel and chop the @red onion{1} into 3cm chunks too. Coat them in a splash of @olive oil{splash}, a pinch of @salt{pinch} and some @ground black pepper{} before roasting for ~{20-25%minutes} until golden-brown.

Meanwhile, boil a large #pot{} of water with a pinch of @salt{pinch}. Once it comes to a gentle boil add the @quinoa{1/2%cup} and cook for around ~{12%minutes}. Take a bit out to test it - it should be soft but with a hint of firmness left in the middle. Drain your quinoa completely in a #fine mesh sieve{} (so it doesn't fall through the holes!).

> If you cook quinoa in a small amount of water you need to rinse it first to improve the flavour. We've suggested using a big pot of water so it cooks and rinses at the same time, due to the fact that it can move around in the water. Easy!

Remove the core from the @red pepper{1/2} and cut it lengthways into thin slices. Now chop it widthways to make tiny squares. Cut the @halloumi{1/2} into thick slices (approx. 1 1/2cm) and grate over half of the @lemon{1/2} zest.

Heat a splash of @olive oil{splash} in a #non-stick frying pan{} on medium heat and once hot add the @diced chorizo{1}. Cook your chorizo for around ~{4%minutes} until slightly crispy at the edges, then remove and keep to the side (but leave all the oil in the pan).

With the pan still on medium heat add in your halloumi slices. Cook for ~{2%minutes} on each side until they are golden and blistered, then remove and chop into little pieces.

Your sweet potato and onion should be just about cooked now, so take it out of your oven and put into a large #bowl{}. Add your chorizo, drained quinoa, halloumi, red pepper and a few handfuls of @baby spinach{1/2%cups}.

Grate in the remaining lemon zest. Chop your lemon in half and squeeze over some juice, add a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle} and gently toss your ingredients with your fingers.

> Do this just before serving your jumble and don't toss it for more than 10 seconds (i.e. be gentle), otherwise it'll mess up your spinach leaves.

Scoop out as much jumble as you can devour and get stuck in!